article.description: Brandie Hoskins had 17 points and 11 assists, and Ohio State upset No. 12 Minnesota 76-62 Thursday night.
article.headline: Buckeyes shoot 69 percent in upset
article.linkText: Buckeyes beat Gophers, in third place in Big Ten
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota officials might need to spend the
night combing through Ohio State's locker room to make sure nothing
is missing after the Buckeyes' sticky-fingered display Thursday
night.

Ohio State (No. 25 AP) had 16 steals and forced 19 Minnesota
turnovers in a 76-62 upset over the 12-ranked Gophers.

The Buckeyes (18-8, 10-5 Big Ten) used a smothering defense to
blow open a close game with a 17-3 run midway through the second
half. They did it without taking a shot longer than 5 feet during
the span, adding to their 68.9 percent shooting mark from the
field.

"We extended our defense a little bit in the second half, and
that created some timely steals that led to quick baskets," Ohio
State coach Jim Foster said.

The Buckeyes frustrated Minnesota with pressure on the ball and
quick feet that helped shut down the Gophers' passing lanes,
triggering numerous fast breaks that led to an 18-for-23 team
shooting performance in the second half.

"The press bothered us a lot," Minnesota coach Pam Borton
said. "When that happens, my philosophy is that you need to play
defense. You need to get stops and you have to rely on your defense
to get you through those spells. But I think we have stopped taking
pride in our defense in the last few games."

All five Ohio State starters scored in double figures, led by
freshman guard Brandie Hoskins, who had 17 points and posted
season-highs with 11 assists and six steals.

"She's shown spurts," said Foster. "She's a freshman and
packaging it all together and processing it all ... she's starting
to become a more consistent player on both ends of the floor for
us."

The win, coupled with losses by Iowa and Michigan State, helped
Ohio State break a four-way tie and take sole possession of third
place in the Big Ten.

LaToya Turner scored 16 points and Jessica Davenport added 15
for the Buckeyes, while Kim Wilburn and Caity Matter chipped in 10
points apiece.

The Gophers started strong and held a 21-13 lead with nine
minutes to play in the first half, but Hoskins hit a pair of
3-pointers and scored 10 points in a 17-2 run that put the Buckeyes
on top 30-23 and they never trailed again.

"We knew they were going to come out strong against us," said
Minnesota center Janel McCarville, who led the Gophers (20-6, 9-6)
with 19 points.

"We always talk about who's going to throw the first punch, and
we thought tonight we really had to. I thought we did -- they were
stumbling a bit, but we didn't take advantage of it," McCarville
said. "They came right back at us and shoved it down our throats
and we couldn't recover."

The Gophers were playing their fifth game without senior Lindsay
Whalen, their leading scorer with an average 20.7 points per game.
She broke two bones in her right hand on Feb. 12 in a game at Ohio
State, but could return in time for the NCAA Tournament.

Borton said Whalen's absence was evident in many ways.

"It's a lot different without her," Borton said. "She's our
best ballhandler, our floor leader, assists leader, our
second-leading rebounder. It takes awhile to adjust to life without
her. Right now, I feel like we could spend three hours in the gym
practicing the basics."
